x4freetext: Two GANIL cyclotrons
A 1.48 mg/cm2 and a 8.25 mg/cm2 thick polypropylene
target (CH2CHCH3)n (density of 0.896 g/cm3).
The 10,11C secondary beams were produced
successively by fragmentation of a 95A. MeV 12C beam
delivered by the two GANIL cyclotrons, on a 1710 mg/cm2
(1930 mg/cm2 for 11C) thick carbon production target
located between the two superconducting solenoids of
the SISSI device (superconducting intense source for
secondary ions).
The events considered to build the
kinematic spectra, and afterward to extract the
(p,p) cross sections, are those for which there is a
proton in coincidence with the heavy ejectile and a
particle detected in both "CATS" (see detector)
providing the incident trajectory and the beam profile.
The excitation energy spectra are calculated from the
kinematic properties of the scattered protons.
The experimental apparatus
MUST is an array of eight three-stage telescopes,
6 x 6 cm2 each. The first stage is a 300 mu-m thick,
double-sided Si-strip detector, the second 3 mm
thick Si(Li); the third stage of 1.5 cm thick CsI
detector.
Two position-sensitive detectors - the low
pressure multiwire trajectory chambers CATS ("chambres
a trajectoires de Saclay",  Trajectory Chambers of
Saclay) - were used to improve the definition of the
position of the incoming ion on the target.
This results in a total systematic error
of +-6%, which is the main error on the normalization
of the extracted elastic and inelastic differential
cross sections. They come from the detection:
* efficiency and reconstruction process, which gives
+- 3% total uncertainty (including the effect of the
subtraction of the background,+-1%);
* the target thickness,+- 5%; and
* the number of incident particles, +-2%.
Statistical uncertainty
The microscopic nucleus-nucleon interaction used to
analyze the elastic scattering on protons is described.
It is calculated using the microscopic, complex, and
parameter-free Jeukenne-Lejeune-Mahaux (JLM) potential.
The theoretical ground state and transition densities
of 10,11C provided by the AMD model and by the
Hartree-Fock with BCS correlations (HF+BCS) and
quasiparticle random phase approximation (QRPA)
formalism are examined. They are used to generate the
microscopic JLM potential included in the (p,p`)
calculations.
Data were received from Dr. V.Lapoux
Entry approved by Dr. V.Lapoux
